  "assets": [
    {
      "assetId": "phys.therm.specific-heat/worked_example/WE-1",
      "kind": "worked_example",
      "conceptId": "phys.therm.specific-heat",
      "title": "(Concrete — direct application)",
      "content": "### WE-1 (Concrete — direct application)\n\n**Scenario:** A 2.0 kg block of copper (c = 385 J/(kg·K)) is heated from 20°C to 120°C by a 500 W electric heater. How long does the heater need to run?\n\n**Step 1 — Heat required.**\nQ = mcΔT = 2.0 × 385 × 100 = 77 000 J = 77 kJ.\n\n**Step 2 — Time at 500 W.**\nP = Q/t → t = Q/P = 77 000 / 500 = 154 s ≈ 2 min 34 s.\n\n**Answer:** 154 seconds.\n\n---",
      "localKey": "WE-1",
      "language": "en",
      "refs": [],
      "span": {
        "file": "docs/curriculum/blueprints/phys.therm.specific-heat.md",
        "startLine": 46,
        "endLine": 92
      }
    },
    {
      "assetId": "phys.therm.specific-heat/worked_example/WE-2",
      "kind": "worked_example",
      "conceptId": "phys.therm.specific-heat",
      "title": "(Bridging — comparing materials)",
      "content": "### WE-2 (Bridging — comparing materials)\n\n**Scenario:** 1.0 kg of water and 1.0 kg of iron, both initially at 20°C, each absorb 50 kJ of heat. Find the final temperature of each.\n\n**Water (c = 4186 J/(kg·K)):**\nΔT_water = Q/(mc) = 50 000 / (1.0 × 4186) = 11.9°C → T_f = 31.9°C.\n\n**Iron (c = 450 J/(kg·K)):**\nΔT_iron = 50 000 / (1.0 × 450) = 111.1°C → T_f = 131.1°C.\n\n**Comparison:** The same heat raises iron's temperature ~9× more than water's. This is why iron cookware gets dangerously hot while water in a pot barely warms up; why water is used as a coolant; and why coastal climates are more moderate than inland (sea buffers temperature).\n\n**Answer:** Water → 31.9°C; Iron → 131.1°C.\n\n---",
      "localKey": "WE-2",
      "language": "en",
      "refs": [],
      "span": {
        "file": "docs/curriculum/blueprints/phys.therm.specific-heat.md",
        "startLine": 46,
        "endLine": 92
      }
    },
    {
      "assetId": "phys.therm.specific-heat/worked_example/WE-3",
      "kind": "worked_example",
      "conceptId": "phys.therm.specific-heat",
      "title": "(Abstract — Dulong-Petit check)",
      "content": "### WE-3 (Abstract — Dulong-Petit check)\n\n**Apply Dulong-Petit:** Copper has molar mass M = 63.5 g/mol and measured c = 385 J/(kg·K). Verify against the Dulong-Petit prediction.\n\n**C_mol (measured):** c × M = 385 × 0.0635 = 24.4 J/(mol·K).\n\n**Dulong-Petit prediction:** C_mol = 3R = 3 × 8.314 = 24.9 J/(mol·K).\n\n**Agreement:** 24.4 vs. 24.9 — within 2%. The classical equipartition theorem gives each atom 3 vibrational degrees of freedom (each with kT/2 PE + kT/2 KE) → U = 3k_BT per atom = 3RT per mole → C_mol = 3R. ✓\n\n**Limitation:** Dulong-Petit fails for very light elements (diamond, C: measured C_mol ≈ 6 J/(mol·K) at room temperature) and at low T — quantum effects (Einstein/Debye models needed). These limitations are beyond this topic.\n\n---",
      "localKey": "WE-3",
      "language": "en",
      "refs": [],
      "span": {
        "file": "docs/curriculum/blueprints/phys.therm.specific-heat.md",
        "startLine": 46,
        "endLine": 92
      }
    },
    {
      "assetId": "phys.therm.specific-heat/misconception/MC-MORE-HEAT-MEANS-MORE-TEMPERATURE",
      "kind": "misconception",
      "conceptId": "phys.therm.specific-heat",
      "title": "**Trigger signal:** Student says \"I added more heat so the temperature must have risen more — heat and temperature are proportional regardless of material or mass.",
      "content": "### MC-MORE-HEAT-MEANS-MORE-TEMPERATURE\n\n**Trigger signal:** Student says \"I added more heat so the temperature must have risen more — heat and temperature are proportional regardless of material or mass.\"\n\n**Conflict evidence [P28]:** \"50 kJ to 1 kg water vs. 50 kJ to 1 kg iron (WE-2): same heat, same mass. If heat and temperature change were simply proportional, both should rise the same amount. Do they?\"\n\n*Water: +11.9°C. Iron: +111°C. Same heat, ~9× different temperature rise.*\n\n**Bridge text [P30]:** \"Temperature change depends on THREE things: heat added (Q), mass (m), and specific heat capacity (c). ΔT = Q/(mc). For the same Q and m, a material with high c (water) shows small ΔT; a material with low c (iron) shows large ΔT. The material's ability to 'absorb' heat without changing temperature is encoded in c.\"\n\n**Replacement text [P31]:** \"Heat is the input; temperature change is the output; specific heat capacity is the transfer function connecting them. Doubling Q doubles ΔT for the same material. Doubling c halves ΔT for the same Q and m. Doubling m halves ΔT. All three variables matter — not just Q.\"\n\n**Discrimination pairs [P33]:**\n- \"100 J into 0.1 kg water vs. 100 J into 0.1 kg copper: which heats up more?\" → Copper (c = 385 vs. 4186) — ΔT_copper ≈ 2.6°C; ΔT_water ≈ 0.24°C.\n- \"Same material, same ΔT, double the mass: how much heat needed?\" → Double Q. ΔT = Q/(mc) → Q = mcΔT. Doubling m doubles Q.\n\n**s6_path:** \"Q = mcΔT — three factors control ΔT, not one.\"\n\n---",
      "localKey": "MC-MORE-HEAT-MEANS-MORE-TEMPERATURE",
      "language": "en",
      "refs": [
        "MC-MORE-HEAT-MEANS-MORE-TEMPERATURE"
      ],
      "span": {
        "file": "docs/curriculum/blueprints/phys.therm.specific-heat.md",
        "startLine": 3,
        "endLine": 23
      }
    },
    {
      "assetId": "phys.therm.specific-heat/misconception/MC-HIGH-TEMPERATURE-MEANS-HIGH-HEAT-CONTENT",
      "kind": "misconception",
      "conceptId": "phys.therm.specific-heat",
      "title": "**Trigger signal:** Student says \"the iron at 131°C has more heat in it than the water at 32°C because it's hotter.",
      "content": "### MC-HIGH-TEMPERATURE-MEANS-HIGH-HEAT-CONTENT\n\n**Trigger signal:** Student says \"the iron at 131°C has more heat in it than the water at 32°C because it's hotter.\"\n\n**Conflict evidence [P28]:** \"Both objects started at 20°C and absorbed exactly 50 kJ. Which has 'more heat' in it — the iron or the water?\"\n\n*Both absorbed 50 kJ — the same amount. The iron is hotter, but not because it has more energy; it has the same energy but a lower capacity to absorb it without rising in temperature.*\n\n**Bridge text [P30]:** \"Temperature measures thermal intensity (heat flow direction); heat content (internal energy) measures total thermal energy stored. High temperature doesn't mean high energy — it means the material has relatively little capacity for more energy (low c) or relatively little mass. A spark has very high temperature but negligible heat content.\"\n\n**Replacement text [P31]:** \"Internal energy U = mcT (rough model — more precisely: U = ∫mc dT). At the same temperature, a larger mass or higher-c material has more internal energy. At the same added energy, a lower-c material rises to a higher temperature. High temperature and high heat content are different things — both relate to U but through different factors.\"\n\n**Discrimination pairs [P33]:**\n- \"A match flame (≈2000°C) vs. a bathtub of warm water (≈40°C): which can melt more ice?\" → Bathtub — vastly more total thermal energy despite lower temperature.\n- \"Two copper blocks: 1 kg at 200°C and 2 kg at 100°C. Which has more internal energy above 20°C?\" → 1 kg: U = 1 × 385 × 180 = 69300 J. 2 kg: U = 2 × 385 × 80 = 61600 J. Hotter block has slightly more — both factors (mass and ΔT above reference) contribute.\n\n**s6_path:** \"Temperature is the 'level'; internal energy is the 'volume'. Same level (T) with different tanks (m, c) means different volumes of stored energy.\"\n\n---",
      "localKey": "MC-HIGH-TEMPERATURE-MEANS-HIGH-HEAT-CONTENT",
      "language": "en",
      "refs": [
        "MC-HIGH-TEMPERATURE-MEANS-HIGH-HEAT-CONTENT"
      ],
